So what I also really need then is a system that can control all this properly. And make sure things are happening. Right now I use hcom with something called tezwiz as a shell / terminal to interact with it cleanly. What I need then is to be able properly overview the system while it works. Right now I just get messages in an inbox and can talk to all the AI at once or individually. But that feels lacking now that the system is more complex. Any ideas on how that would look?
Architected mission control dashboard replacing inbox paradigm

The reason the inbox feels lacking is that it's the wrong paradigm now, not just too small. An inbox is built for messages — linear, reactive, everything weighted equally. What a complex live system needs is mission control — a shift from reading a stream to observing state and intervening by exception. You stop consuming every message and start watching a system that only pulls your attention when it actually needs you. That reframe drives everything below.

The key realization: you're not always going to be staring at it, so it needs three layers, not one:

1. Ambient / push (when you're away). Only the things that genuinely can't wait reach you off-screen: a budget breach, everything halted, an irreversible-action approval gate, the kill-switch tripping. This is the "you need to look now" channel — and it ties directly to the degradation policy (what happens when the operator's absent). Everything else waits.

2. The dashboard (when you're at the machine). This is the new core, and given you live in a terminal, it should be a TUI — think k9s for a Kubernetes cluster, or htop, or lazygit. A multi-pane live view:

    A vitals bar across the top — one-glance health: tasks in-flight / blocked / awaiting-approval, today's spend vs. budget, agents alive/working/idle/broken, validator up/down. Two seconds tells you if the system is flowing or wedged.
    The roster panel — every agent across your three tiers, what it's working on, a live heartbeat dot (green pulsing = alive, red = gone silent). This is your "who's doing what," and it makes a hung agent visible instantly, which the inbox never could.
    The flight board (center) — active tasks and their state: in-flight, blocked-on-dependency, waiting-approval, halted. The departure-board metaphor from the transit stuff actually fits perfectly here — tasks arriving and departing, with what's stuck highlighted.
    The attention queue (right) — this is the heart of the whole thing. Only items that need a human decision: pending approval gates, validator halts awaiting your call, budget warnings, escalations, silent agents. When it's empty, nothing needs you and you can walk away. This panel is the direct answer to the "operator is a finite bottleneck" problem — it's triage for you, the exact inverse of an undifferentiated inbox.
    A filterable event stream along the bottom — the structured trace scrolling by. Your current inbox becomes just one filtered view of this, not the whole interface.

Then drill-down and intervention on top: select any task → see its full causal chain (the trace tree you already have from observability), its cost, its history, why it halted. Select any agent → its lane, recent work, heartbeat history. And keybindings to act: approve/deny a gate, kill a runaway task, pull or resume an agent, bump a budget, override a false halt.

3. Conversational (preserved, but demoted). Talking to the agents — collectively or individually — doesn't go away. It becomes one mode you drop into from a panel, not the entire interface. Select an agent, hit a key, you're in dialogue with it; back out, you're in mission control again.

How it sits on what you have: hcom stays as the inter-agent comms and shared-state layer — the control plane is a lens that reads from hcom + the event store and writes interventions back. tezwiz can host it or it runs standalone in a pane.

What to build it with: given you're a Python dev who likes dark/flat/polished interfaces, Textual is almost purpose-built for this — it's the modern Python TUI framework, does reactive multi-pane dashboards, mouse support, genuinely beautiful flat aesthetics, and can even run in a browser if you ever want that. k9s is the mental model for the feel; Textual is how you'd build that feel in your stack. (If you ever wanted it as a desktop app instead, your PySide6 experience would carry over — but for system monitoring, a TUI is more idiomatic and fits the terminal workflow you already have.)

The one-line version of the shift: stop reading what the system said, start watching what it's doing — and let it interrupt you only when a decision is genuinely yours to make.

