What about all the talk I hear about connecting Claude code and obsidian, it feels like that's more for the user's sake and not the code. Like does Claude code really benefit from obsidian?
Weighed user convenience against genuine agent capability benefits

It's genuinely mixed, but it leans more "for the agent" than people give it credit for — the skepticism isn't crazy though.

Where it actually helps the agent:

    Obsidian vaults are just structured markdown with wikilinks and tags — that's a graph, and MCP servers exposing that graph let Claude Code query relationships ([[note]] links, backlinks, tag clusters) instead of grepping flat files. That's real retrieval structure, not decoration.
    Persistent notes act as long-term memory across sessions — closer to what you're doing with HPOM/hcom than a nice-to-have. An agent that can read "decisions I made last week and why" avoids re-litigating settled questions.
    Daily notes / changelogs give the agent a timeline it otherwise has to reconstruct from git log and guesswork.

Where the skepticism is fair:

    A lot of "Claude Code + Obsidian" setups are really just "dump my README into fancier markdown" — the agent would've been fine with plain files in the repo. The graph/backlink structure only pays off if you're actually using Obsidian's linking conventions, not just writing notes in an Obsidian folder.
    Obsidian's real strengths — visual graph view, plugins, UI for humans skimming — do nothing for the model. It reads text either way, so 80% of the pitch (the experience) is for the human.
    If your notes aren't densely cross-linked, you're paying integration complexity for what plain flat-file context would've given you.

Rule of thumb: it's worth it when the vault is a genuinely linked knowledge graph the agent can traverse for relationships (like a proper emergence-style memory store); it's cargo-culting when it's just "notes, but in Obsidian."

